node.statement: CASE 1b - Orbit growth under <g_2, g_3>. Since g_2(B) is not equal to B and g_3(B) is not equal to B, the orbit of B under <g_2, g_3> contains multiple blocks. ANALYSIS: Let s = |orbit of B under H|. Then s * |B| = N. Since |B| >= 4 + n (contains {1,3,4,6,a_i}), and N = 6+n+k+m, we have s <= (6+n+k+m)/(4+n). For s >= 2 and the orbit to work consistently, the action of g_3 must permute blocks in a compatible way. But g_3 maps 6 -> 2 (from B to g_2(B)) and 2 -> 3 (from g_2(B) to B), so g_3 mixes elements across blocks B and g_2(B). This forces g_3(B) to overlap both, contradiction.
